title: [Evaluation] Use the latest official SWE-Bench Dockerization for evaluation
body:
**What is the problem that this fixes or functionality that this introduces? Does it fix any open issues?**

In https://github.com/princeton-nlp/SWE-bench/blob/main/docs/20240627_docker/README.md, SWE-Bench officially introduced a dockerized implementation of SWE-Bench evaluation where **"99.78% (2289/2294) of SWE-bench tasks and 100% (300/300) of SWE-bench Lite tasks consistently resolve correctly with the ground truth solution."**

This provides more reliable evaluation for SWE-Bench problems.

**Give a brief summary of what the PR does, explaining any non-trivial design decisions**

1. Integrate SWE-Bench docker into OpenDevin eco-system.
2. Provide a script for the user to pull existing instance-level images (for SWE-Bench Lite) that are pre-build to speed up evaluation. If built from scratch, a few instances might be impacted by the network connection, and the whole `eval_infer.sh` script needs to be re-run several times.

TODO:
- [x] Running on some existing output (e.g., v1.6, v1.6-no-hint output) to measure performance.

UPDATE:
1. `v1.6-no-hint` performance drop from 58 resolved to 57 resolved. The new harness got an additional instance `psf__requests-2674` passed, but two old `'django__django-16379', and 'django__django-13590'` failed. Upon further investigation, it seems this is the issue: https://github.com/princeton-nlp/SWE-bench/issues/165. Am working on a fixed.
2. With this fix https://github.com/princeton-nlp/SWE-bench/pull/166 (included in the PR!), **`v1.6-no-hint` performance improves from 58 resolved to 59 resolved (19.7%)**!
4. `v1.6` (with hint) performance improves from 70 resolved to 73 resolved with the harness in this PR!
5. I think this PR is good to go!

**Other references**

```suggestion
**UPDATE (7/1/2024): We now support the official SWE-Bench dockerized evaluation as announced [here](https://github.com/princeton-nlp/SWE-bench/blob/main/docs/20240627_docker/README.md).**
```
IIRC they say how much space we should expect it to take, I wonder if we can say that too, explicitly, to make it clear for readers.

If simply calculate the sum of docker size - it will need 2T. But my disk is certainly less than 2T and it worked since there's a lot of layer re-use, which makes the number hard to estimate. Maybe we can just say 500G-1T is a safe number?


```suggestion
If you want to save disk space a bit (e.g., with ~50GB free disk space) while speed up the image pre-build process, you can pull the environment-level docker images:
```
